APL support Geoff Streeter 2012-01-04

APL was initially an overstruck language. The original APL terminal was an IBM golfball with a specially designed golfball. This meant that characters could be overstruck to produce other characters. This gave APL a richness of primitives which is still powerful today. Overstrikes were always independent of order.
APLs have extended this into a number of dialects. Let us try to support lots of them. Together with some that have not been used yet. Some traditional ones are not included.
